const e="Gandhari",a=[{title:"Birth and Early Life",content:"Gandhari was the princess of Gandhara, born to King Subala. She was admired for her beauty, wisdom, and strong sense of virtue from an early age."},{title:"Marriage to Dhritarashtra",content:"Gandhari was married to Dhritarashtra, the blind prince of Hastinapura. Out of deep devotion, she blindfolded herself permanently so that she would share her husband’s blindness and never see the world he could not."},{title:"Motherhood of the Kauravas",content:"Through great austerities and blessings, Gandhari gave birth to a hundred sons, known as the Kauravas, and a daughter, Dushala. Despite being a mother of so many, she lived a life of simplicity and sacrifice."},{title:"Role in the Mahabharata",content:"Gandhari tried her best to guide her sons toward righteousness but was often ignored due to Shakuni’s influence and Duryodhana’s arrogance. She often warned them of the consequences of their enmity with the Pandavas."},{title:"The Kurukshetra War and Grief",content:"The war brought immense sorrow to Gandhari as she witnessed the deaths of her hundred sons. Despite her grief, she maintained her composure and accepted the outcome as destiny, though her heart was shattered by the loss."},{title:"Curse on Krishna",content:"In her anguish, Gandhari cursed Krishna, holding him responsible for not preventing the war despite his power. She prophesied the destruction of the Yadava clan, which later came true."},{title:"Later Life and Renunciation",content:"After the war, Gandhari withdrew from royal life, renouncing worldly pleasures. Alongside Dhritarashtra and Kunti, she retired to the forest to lead a life of penance."},{title:"Death and Legacy",content:"Gandhari met her end in a forest fire along with her husband and Kunti. She is remembered as an epitome of loyalty, sacrifice, and tragic motherhood in the Mahabharata."}],t={name:e,fullBiography:a};export{t as default,a as fullBiography,e as name};
